Comment: I started with an open mind and was vaguely thinking about a four move checkmate.
He opened with a common defense to a pawn at e4.
I moved out my bishop, continuing my planned attack.
He moved out his knight, also a common defense, but this time realizing my intentions.
I moved out a pawn preparing to threaten the knight with my queen-side bishop.
He moved out his king-side bishop in order to gain a vantage point, and control part of the middle.
I developed my queen to threaten the knight, however, not planning to attack.
He moved out a pawn to open his queen on the left side.
I moved my black bishop to threaten an attack.
He moved out his pawn, forcing a decision, either retreat or attack and sacrifice.
Sacrifice.
He decides to attack with queen, knowing I wouldn't attack.
I moved this way, not my best, In order to stay unpredictable and not be too easy to notice.
He obviously took the queen, after a few seconds though.
I moved out my knight, rethinking my plan.
He opened up his bishop, to threaten
I moved out my pawn to open up a space for my knights next move.
He decided it would also be in his best interest to attack that pawn, this small mistake, allowed me to learn what he prioritized.
I took the pawn, planning the next move out.
He threatened my remaining bishop with his.
